WEBVTT

00:08.225 --> 00:08.399
.

00:08.443 --> 00:12.099
[cell phone alarm ringing]

00:12.142 --> 00:14.362
[beeping stops]

00:17.365 --> 00:20.716
[soft vocalizing]

00:20.759 --> 00:23.719
[The Oh Hellos'
"Hello My Old Heart"]

00:23.762 --> 00:28.593
♪

00:28.637 --> 00:30.813
- ♪ Hello, my old heart

00:30.856 --> 00:34.077
♪ How have you been?

00:34.121 --> 00:39.387
♪ Are you still there
inside my chest? ♪

00:39.430 --> 00:42.085
♪ I've been so worried

00:42.129 --> 00:44.696
♪ You've been so still

00:44.740 --> 00:49.788
♪ Barely beating at all

00:49.832 --> 00:52.139
♪ Oh

00:52.182 --> 00:54.706
♪ Don't leave me here alone

00:54.750 --> 00:58.101
♪ Don't tell me that we've
grown for having loved ♪

00:58.145 --> 01:00.408
♪ A little while

01:00.451 --> 01:02.366
♪ Oh, oh-oh

01:02.410 --> 01:05.543
♪ I don't wanna be alone

01:05.587 --> 01:07.371
♪ I wanna find a home

01:07.415 --> 01:11.245
♪ And I wanna share it
with you ♪

01:11.288 --> 01:14.596
- Good morning s--

01:14.639 --> 01:17.686
- A cruel person wrote these.

01:17.729 --> 01:21.429
- A cruel person is going
to put you back in bed.

01:25.824 --> 01:28.827
- Do you remember how much I
loved this bed when we got it?

01:28.871 --> 01:30.525
- I do.
- Hmm.

01:30.568 --> 01:33.223
Now I want to set it on fire
and laugh while it burns.

01:33.267 --> 01:35.704
- That sounds dangerous,
and bed rest is important.

01:35.747 --> 01:39.447
It prevents the cervix from--
- From having a life.

01:39.490 --> 01:42.450
Max, my cervix is so bored.

01:44.843 --> 01:48.369
Thank you for doing this.

01:48.412 --> 01:49.761
All of it.

01:53.548 --> 01:55.245
How's the couch?

01:56.681 --> 01:58.335
- Really good.
- Hmm?

01:58.379 --> 01:59.597
- Yeah, it's a little bit
better than the bed,

01:59.641 --> 02:02.122
to be honest.
- [laughs]

02:04.733 --> 02:07.388
I want to be ready, Max.

02:07.431 --> 02:10.347
I want to want you back.

02:10.391 --> 02:13.307
I'm just--I'm not...

02:16.223 --> 02:17.833
- I got all the time
in the world.

02:20.923 --> 02:23.882
[Nathaniel Rateliff's
"You Worry Me"]

02:23.926 --> 02:30.324
♪

02:30.367 --> 02:32.587
- ♪ I'm all right today

02:32.630 --> 02:34.806
♪ You gonna find a way
to cross ♪

02:34.850 --> 02:36.765
♪ And you gonna get there

02:36.808 --> 02:39.768
♪

02:39.811 --> 02:42.379
♪ And I'm on fire today

02:42.423 --> 02:47.645
♪ Ain't no water here to calm
or even put me out ♪

02:49.386 --> 02:51.736
♪ I'll find a better way

02:51.780 --> 02:55.175
♪ Am I crazy, or the wind is
gonna blow me down? ♪

02:55.218 --> 02:58.221
- Do you mind if I ask how long
your foot's been hurting?

02:58.265 --> 03:01.616
- It's nothing.
I'm fine.

03:02.530 --> 03:04.401
- I'm a doctor at New Amsterdam

03:04.445 --> 03:06.838
right across the street.
- No.

03:06.882 --> 03:07.970
- Maybe you could
take a walk with me.

03:08.013 --> 03:09.537
I could have a look at that.

03:09.580 --> 03:11.800
- Maybe you could
leave me alone.

03:11.843 --> 03:13.497
- Your foot is badly infected.

03:13.541 --> 03:14.890
If you don't do something
about it, it's going to get

03:14.933 --> 03:17.240
a lot worse.
- Can you get away from me?

03:21.940 --> 03:27.685
♪

03:27.729 --> 03:31.298
- I love soil.
Do you want to know why?

03:31.341 --> 03:33.778
- I am at the edge
of my metaphorical seat.

03:33.822 --> 03:35.867
- Because it contains
mycobacterium vaccae,

03:35.911 --> 03:38.000
which has been proven to
promote serotonin production,

03:38.043 --> 03:40.263
which acts as
a natural antidepressant.

03:40.307 --> 03:42.526
- So does that hat.

03:42.570 --> 03:43.527
- Can't bring me down,
my friend.

03:43.571 --> 03:44.702
Not today.

03:44.746 --> 03:46.878
The HCC has funded my proposal.

03:46.922 --> 03:48.837
After two years,
they funded it!

03:48.880 --> 03:51.274
- For the community garden?
- Yes, exactly.

03:51.318 --> 03:52.841
You know, horticultural therapy
dates back

03:52.884 --> 03:54.712
to ancient Mesopotamia,
and--uh,

03:54.756 --> 03:56.888
oh, my gosh, are those your
little homemade Indian donuts?

03:56.932 --> 03:59.500
- They are not donuts.
They are laddus.

03:59.543 --> 04:00.936
- Well, I don't mind
if I "laddu."

04:00.979 --> 04:05.680
- They are not for you.
They are for someone else.

04:05.723 --> 04:07.812
- Not the girl from
the coffee shop, though.

04:07.856 --> 04:09.249
- Her name is Ella.

04:09.292 --> 04:10.554
It's my gesture of gratitude

04:10.598 --> 04:12.295
for someone
who showed me kindness.

04:12.339 --> 04:13.731
- Okay, let me see
if I got this straight:

04:13.775 --> 04:15.385
you're gonna give pastries
to someone who works

04:15.429 --> 04:17.561
in a pastry shop.
- Laddus are not pastries.

04:17.605 --> 04:19.694
They are sweets.
- Oh.

04:19.737 --> 04:21.913
Well, that doesn't make it
any less weird.

04:21.957 --> 04:24.916
[upbeat music]

04:24.960 --> 04:31.575
♪

04:31.619 --> 04:33.577
Gladys?

04:33.621 --> 04:34.970
Gladys, what is this?

04:35.013 --> 04:39.017
- Volt cola swag.
A gift from the new sponsor.

04:39.061 --> 04:40.758
- What new sponsor?

04:40.802 --> 04:42.934
- For your community garden.

04:42.978 --> 04:45.285
♪

04:45.328 --> 04:48.331
[indistinct conversation]

04:49.811 --> 04:53.075
- Bloom?
What's the urgent page?

04:53.118 --> 04:55.382
- Got an EMS notification

04:55.425 --> 04:56.992
asking to have
thoracic standing by.

04:57.035 --> 04:59.386
- You okay?
- Headache.

04:59.429 --> 05:01.953
[doors slam open]

05:01.997 --> 05:04.782
- 45-year-old man, acute onset
tearing chest pain.

05:04.826 --> 05:07.350
Heart rate 110;
140 over 56, right arm;

05:07.394 --> 05:09.787
100 over palp, left.
Respiration's 18.

05:09.831 --> 05:12.834
Gave him nitro--
- Dissecting aortic aneurysm.

05:14.575 --> 05:17.534
- Mateo?

05:17.578 --> 05:19.754
- Hope you're on
your game today, Floyd.

05:21.843 --> 05:24.324
- Who's--
- Mateo Fernandez.

05:24.367 --> 05:26.064
- The cardiothoracic
from Baptist?

05:26.108 --> 05:28.371
- Yeah.
- Isn't this week--

05:28.415 --> 05:30.678
- Yeah.
Hey, get Max down here now.

05:30.721 --> 05:32.462
- Oh.

05:32.506 --> 05:35.770
- Okay, as I fit you
for the radiation mask,

05:35.813 --> 05:39.339
remember you have to keep
absolutely still.

05:39.382 --> 05:41.428
- I always found stillness
to be a highly overrated

05:41.471 --> 05:44.431
human ability.
- Consider it practice

05:44.474 --> 05:46.781
for when we aim high energy
external beam radiation

05:46.824 --> 05:49.000
at the cancer in your throat.

05:49.044 --> 05:52.526
If you move then,
you die.

05:52.569 --> 05:54.528
Has anyone ever told you
you would make

05:54.571 --> 05:56.486
a great James Bond villain?

05:56.530 --> 05:57.487
[cell phone vibrating]

05:57.531 --> 05:59.489
Uh, Max, you cannot move.

05:59.533 --> 06:01.361
- Right.

06:01.404 --> 06:03.754
So, uh, come here often?

06:03.798 --> 06:05.974
- That includes your mouth.

06:06.017 --> 06:08.063
- All of it? Because--
- Do I have to remind you

06:08.106 --> 06:09.978
that you need a throat
to make jokes?

06:12.720 --> 06:14.069
[cell phone vibrates]

06:14.112 --> 06:16.724
- Relax.

06:16.767 --> 06:18.421
You can close your eyes
if you'd like.

06:18.465 --> 06:19.422
[cell phone vibrates]

06:19.466 --> 06:21.424
Stay still, Max.

06:21.468 --> 06:24.514
[tense music]

06:24.558 --> 06:29.389
♪

06:29.432 --> 06:30.564
Done.

06:30.607 --> 06:32.870
[cell phone vibrates]

06:32.914 --> 06:35.786
I think it's fair to say that
was torture for both of us.

06:37.919 --> 06:39.964
- If my cancer gets
anyone else killed besides me,

06:40.008 --> 06:42.967
then I'm really going
to be upset.

06:43.011 --> 06:44.752
I got the 911.

06:44.795 --> 06:46.057
- This week's the annual
conference

06:46.101 --> 06:47.798
of Cardiothoracic Surgeons
in San Diego.

06:47.842 --> 06:50.192
Everyone goes.
All of my attendings are there.

06:50.235 --> 06:51.715
One unlucky surgeon
stays behind

06:51.759 --> 06:53.021
at each hospital to cover.

06:53.064 --> 06:54.718
It's me here,
It's Fernandez at Baptist,

06:54.762 --> 06:56.720
but only one of us has
a dissecting aortic aneurysm.

06:56.764 --> 06:58.635
- And since he's here,

06:58.679 --> 07:00.550
I'm guessing no one's
covering Baptist.

07:00.594 --> 07:01.899
- They still have general
surgeons, transplant surgeons.

07:01.943 --> 07:03.423
- Yeah, they can't cover
for Fernandez.

07:03.466 --> 07:04.641
- You want a gynecologist
tagging in

07:04.685 --> 07:06.556
on your heart surgery?

07:08.950 --> 07:10.560
- How can Baptist run
their hospital

07:10.604 --> 07:12.170
without
a cardiothoracic surgeon?

07:12.214 --> 07:13.824
- They can't.
Which means they're no longer

07:13.868 --> 07:14.956
a level-one trauma center.

07:14.999 --> 07:16.436
- Without
cardiothoracic backup,

07:16.479 --> 07:17.915
they can't treat
myocardial infarctions,

07:17.959 --> 07:20.483
car accidents, GSWs--
they can't accept ambulances.

07:20.527 --> 07:21.571
- Guys, we're gonna have
to pick up

07:21.615 --> 07:22.833
Baptist's full ambulance load.

07:22.877 --> 07:24.182
- I knew you were
gonna say that.

07:24.226 --> 07:25.227
- They'd do it for us.
- Would they?

07:25.270 --> 07:26.663
- We're short-staffed too.

07:26.707 --> 07:27.969
What about
the network hospitals?

07:28.012 --> 07:29.492
- They'll pick up
the elective admits,

07:29.536 --> 07:30.885
but emergency patients
will die waiting

07:30.928 --> 07:32.495
in cross-town traffic.
We're the closest.

07:32.539 --> 07:34.497
It's on us.
- You really think we can

07:34.541 --> 07:37.065
shoulder their full ED plus all
the cardiothoracic surgeries?

07:37.108 --> 07:38.762
- Just the ones that need
to be done today.

07:38.806 --> 07:40.808
- Yeah, just those.
- Guys, this is what we do.

07:40.851 --> 07:43.245
We help everyone.
Floyd, I trust you

07:43.288 --> 07:45.639
and I believe in you,
so I am only going to do this

07:45.682 --> 07:47.118
if you tell me
you can handle it.

07:47.162 --> 07:48.990
- I can handle it.
- Okay, good,

07:49.033 --> 07:50.948
because if something goes
wrong, we are both on the hook.

07:50.992 --> 07:52.689
- But nothing will go wrong,
all right?

07:52.733 --> 07:53.690
I'll make sure of it.

07:53.734 --> 07:56.127
- ...upstairs, all right?

07:56.171 --> 07:57.868
- Okay.

07:57.912 --> 07:59.479
[elevator dings]

08:03.091 --> 08:03.265
.

08:03.308 --> 08:06.398
- Bloom, we're going to live or
die today based on our ED load.

08:06.442 --> 08:08.052
So, any doc or nurse
standing still in any part

08:08.096 --> 08:10.359
of this hospital
needs to go down and pitch in.

08:10.402 --> 08:12.056
- I'll take it.
- I already hear sirens,

08:12.100 --> 08:13.493
so unfortunately, you're going
to have to miss the rest

08:13.536 --> 08:15.233
of my big pep talk.
- Aw, so sad.

08:15.277 --> 08:17.584
- Iggy, psych wait times
are the longest, so make sure

08:17.627 --> 08:19.890
you get your patients up
to your ward early and often.

08:19.934 --> 08:21.065
- All right.
Good thing psych patients

08:21.109 --> 08:22.502
are so compliant.

08:22.545 --> 08:24.068
- Kapoor, neurology wait times
are second,

08:24.112 --> 08:25.461
so I need you to move
double time today.

08:25.505 --> 08:27.550
- This is my double time.
- Noted.

08:27.594 --> 08:29.552
Sharpe.
- This is a bad idea.

08:29.596 --> 08:31.293
So is sending every
cardiothoracic surgeon

08:31.336 --> 08:32.947
in America to San Diego
at the same time,

08:32.990 --> 08:34.557
but they do it every year.

08:34.601 --> 08:36.907
- Last year was Barcelona.
- I do love sangria.

08:36.951 --> 08:38.605
- This is a bad idea.
- So, are you telling me

08:38.648 --> 08:40.302
that you wouldn't have taken
the extra patients?

08:40.345 --> 08:42.086
- No, I wouldn't have.

08:42.130 --> 08:44.349
- I try to make things
simple, easy.

08:44.393 --> 08:46.264
You know, like a normal person.
- Ah.

08:46.308 --> 08:48.092
- Why do you keep choosing
the hardest road

08:48.136 --> 08:50.268
at every opportunity?

08:50.312 --> 08:52.575
- Better views?

08:52.619 --> 08:55.622
[siren wailing distantly]

08:57.058 --> 08:59.277
- Tall person, how long have
you been with Reynolds?

08:59.321 --> 09:02.106
- Three years.
And it's Nottingham.

09:02.150 --> 09:04.413
- I'm a PGY-6, so--
- Okay, today is not the day

09:04.456 --> 09:06.981
where I'm gonna be polite
and remember your names.

09:07.024 --> 09:09.244
When patients come in,
I'm going to point and yell.

09:09.287 --> 09:11.986
Don't take it personally.
You move on my orders only.

09:12.029 --> 09:15.076
[siren wailing]

09:20.560 --> 09:22.518
- What'd you bring us?
- Adaline Simon.

09:22.562 --> 09:24.128
53-year-old female,
had a pleurodesis

09:24.172 --> 09:26.348
on the books at Baptist.
- Tall person,

09:26.391 --> 09:28.306
take Mrs. Simon
to any empty bed

09:28.350 --> 09:29.569
and get her prepped
for surgery.

09:29.612 --> 09:31.135
- This is Mr. Gold,
47-year-old male

09:31.179 --> 09:32.615
in need of a VATS procedure.

09:32.659 --> 09:35.270
- Casey and brown-haired woman.
Any open bay.

09:35.313 --> 09:37.011
- Name is Sherry Fletcher.
68-year-old female.

09:37.054 --> 09:38.752
She requires a mediastinoscopy.

09:38.795 --> 09:41.624
- Stay with me.
Okay, let's get her inside.

09:43.800 --> 09:47.630
Okay, put Mrs. Fletcher
in bay 23.

09:47.674 --> 09:49.327
Has anybody seen my ibuprofen?

09:49.371 --> 09:50.981
- Tell a nurse to grab you
a bottle from the--

09:51.025 --> 09:53.331
- What I need is for
people to stop taking my stuff.

09:53.375 --> 09:55.682
[ambulance wailing]

09:55.725 --> 09:58.293
Incoming!

09:58.336 --> 10:01.383
[tool buzzing]

10:01.426 --> 10:02.732
- Rib spreader.
- Rib spreader.

10:02.776 --> 10:04.604
- Fair warning: this is being
recorded

10:04.647 --> 10:08.216
so that Dr. Fernandez can see
my technique when he's awake.

10:08.259 --> 10:11.741
- Um, Dr. Reynolds?

10:11.785 --> 10:16.398
Uh, Dr. Bloom asked
me to, um...

10:16.441 --> 10:18.139
- Start with the subject,
then the verb,

10:18.182 --> 10:19.575
and see where the sentence
goes from there.

10:20.837 --> 10:23.361
- The cases from Baptist
are crowding the ED.

10:23.405 --> 10:25.146
There's a pleurodesis.

10:25.189 --> 10:26.756
With your permission,
I was thinking I could grab

10:26.800 --> 10:28.802
a general attending to
supervise and handle it myself.

10:28.845 --> 10:30.673
- Appreciate the enthusiasm,
but prep the patient

10:30.717 --> 10:32.370
and wait for me.

10:32.414 --> 10:33.763
- It's just the ED's awfully
full, and I really think

10:33.807 --> 10:35.678
I can help out--
- You have a very promising

10:35.722 --> 10:37.375
future.
I don't want you in over

10:37.419 --> 10:38.812
your head when
I'm too busy to bail you out.

10:38.855 --> 10:41.205
A mistake like that can
derail your entire career,

10:41.249 --> 10:43.120
so go ahead
and prep the patient,

10:43.164 --> 10:44.556
and I'll get there
when I'm done.

10:45.775 --> 10:48.343
- Yes, sir.

10:48.386 --> 10:49.431
Thank you.

10:51.563 --> 10:53.783
- Baptist's surgeons are on
a flight back from San Diego.

10:53.827 --> 10:56.133
It lands in five hours.
You got this, right?

10:56.177 --> 10:57.613
- [sighs] Do I have a choice?

10:57.657 --> 11:00.224
- I could warp
the space-time continuum.

11:00.268 --> 11:01.704
- Hey, what patient
is that for?

11:01.748 --> 11:03.314
- A homeless woman outside.

11:03.358 --> 11:05.099
- You couldn't find
a patient inside to help?

11:05.142 --> 11:07.492
- If I don't help her,
she's going to lose her foot.

11:07.536 --> 11:09.581
- Send an intern.
- She's skeptical of doctors

11:09.625 --> 11:12.149
and so am I,
so we have an understanding.

11:12.193 --> 11:14.412
I'll be back in five minutes.
- What?

11:14.456 --> 11:17.285
- Sorry, Doc!

11:17.328 --> 11:19.766
[frantic music]

11:19.809 --> 11:22.333
- You and Ella have
an asymmetric power structure.

11:22.377 --> 11:24.422
Giving her a gift
can be misinterpreted

11:24.466 --> 11:27.338
as a deliberate extraction
of reciprocal favors,

11:27.382 --> 11:28.600
sexual or otherwise.

11:28.644 --> 11:32.604
- I see you talked
to Dr. Frome.

11:32.648 --> 11:34.606
Mrs. Monaghan,
I am Dr. Vijay Kapoor

11:34.650 --> 11:36.652
and this is Dr., uh...
- Kao.

11:36.696 --> 11:38.262
- Dr. Kao.

11:38.306 --> 11:41.744
- I'm dizzy.
- I'm so sorry to hear that.

11:41.788 --> 11:43.790
Dizzy can be awful.

11:43.833 --> 11:46.401
Can you explain to me--
what do you mean by dizzy?

11:46.444 --> 11:48.795
- You don't know "dizzy"?

11:48.838 --> 11:51.798
- I do, I do, but I also know
that it means different things

11:51.841 --> 11:54.148
to different people.
- Well, at Baptist,

11:54.191 --> 11:56.280
they understand dizzy.
- That may be true,

11:56.324 --> 11:58.674
but here at New Amsterdam,
I want you to think about

11:58.718 --> 12:01.503
what exactly dizzy
means to you.

12:01.546 --> 12:05.681
- It means dizzy.

12:05.725 --> 12:08.771
- The good news is that
your CT scans are negative

12:08.815 --> 12:11.121
and preliminary lab tests
all look fine.

12:11.165 --> 12:15.299
- She's a good doctor.
- Yes, she is.

12:15.343 --> 12:17.301
So, while I examine
my other patients,

12:17.345 --> 12:20.783
I want you to think about
your kind of dizzy.

12:20.827 --> 12:25.179
♪

12:25.222 --> 12:26.789
- Tell me you're admitting
"dizzy chick."

12:26.833 --> 12:29.792
- I cannot admit anyone
without a proper diagnosis.

12:29.836 --> 12:31.446
And I don't have any yet.

12:33.927 --> 12:35.711
- Maybe we should make it
a multiple choice question?

12:35.755 --> 12:38.758
- We cannot give her choices.
It will influence her answers.

12:38.801 --> 12:41.325
We just need to know
what dizzy means to her,

12:41.369 --> 12:45.199
and we will get our diagnosis.

12:45.242 --> 12:47.462
- So then I call HCC,

12:47.505 --> 12:49.551
and they say I take the money
from Volt Cola

12:49.594 --> 12:50.900
or I can kiss
my garden goodbye.

12:50.944 --> 12:52.815
- More than half
of the sugar kids consume

12:52.859 --> 12:55.470
comes directly from soda.
- I know.

12:55.513 --> 12:57.733
- Volt Cola spends millions
each year to defeat

12:57.777 --> 13:00.257
public health legislation
that could actually help.

13:00.301 --> 13:01.911
- I know.
- So, unless you want to hurry

13:01.955 --> 13:03.826
along the epidemic
of childhood obesity,

13:03.870 --> 13:06.263
then there is no way
you can take their money.

13:06.307 --> 13:07.699
- I know.
- Great.

13:07.743 --> 13:09.701
Now you can focus on
the epidemic of overcrowding

13:09.745 --> 13:11.268
in my ED.

13:11.312 --> 13:13.880
Your psych patients
are in bays 2, 8;

13:13.923 --> 13:17.361
rooms 12, 22, and 28.
Get them out of here.

13:17.405 --> 13:19.450
- Okeydoke, Doc.
[sighing]

13:21.670 --> 13:23.846
- Okay, I'm just gonna check
if the numbing medication

13:23.890 --> 13:25.979
has worked, Tianna.
Can you feel this?

13:26.022 --> 13:27.632
- No.
- How about this?

13:27.676 --> 13:29.330
- Mm-mm.

13:29.373 --> 13:31.636
- She was in pain,
so we called 911.

13:31.680 --> 13:33.377
We didn't want
to take any chances.

13:33.421 --> 13:35.684
- Should we have just
driven her to Baptist?

13:35.727 --> 13:37.338
- No, no.
You did the right thing.

13:37.381 --> 13:39.470
I've read Tianna's file.
I'm all caught up.

13:39.514 --> 13:41.864
- Mommy, you're not watching.
- I am, sweetheart.

13:41.908 --> 13:43.735
- Oh, don't move, Tianna.

13:43.779 --> 13:46.738
I'm just gathering the cells I
need for the biopsy right now.

13:46.782 --> 13:49.480
- Those are gonna tell you
if my cancer's back?

13:49.524 --> 13:50.830
- That's right.

13:54.790 --> 13:58.707
- What's it like when you die?

14:00.622 --> 14:03.016
[gentle music]

14:03.059 --> 14:06.236
- Baby, you don't need
to know that.

14:06.280 --> 14:08.325
That's not going to happen
for a long, long time.

14:08.369 --> 14:10.850
All right, baby girl?

14:10.893 --> 14:12.460
Right, Dr. Sharpe?

14:14.462 --> 14:18.640
- Do you want the elephant
or the tiger Band-Aid?

14:18.683 --> 14:20.947
- Nobody tells me anything.

14:23.645 --> 14:29.303
♪

14:30.957 --> 14:33.785
- Miss me?
- Nope, nope, nope, nope.

14:33.829 --> 14:36.963
I can't afford your help!
- My help is free.

14:38.660 --> 14:40.792
Not taking it is gonna
cost you your foot,

14:40.836 --> 14:44.927
so either way, you're
gonna have to deal with me.

14:44.971 --> 14:47.799
- You're relentless.

14:47.843 --> 14:49.889
- I'm Max.

14:52.500 --> 14:56.373
- I'm Faye.
- It's nice to meet you, Faye.

14:56.417 --> 15:01.944
Okay, take one of these a day
until the bottle is gone.

15:01.988 --> 15:04.947
I have to go, but, uh,

15:04.991 --> 15:06.862
I'll come back to check on you.

15:09.473 --> 15:13.521
- I have a brother
who's very sick.

15:15.523 --> 15:19.614
He won't go to the hospital.

15:19.657 --> 15:23.487
Can you help him too?

15:23.531 --> 15:27.535
- I have a hospital full
of patients who need me.

15:27.578 --> 15:34.629
♪

15:43.725 --> 15:45.640
How can I help?

15:52.038 --> 15:52.255
.

15:52.299 --> 15:55.171
- Faye, I really can't go far.
- We're close.

15:55.215 --> 15:57.260
I promise.

15:57.304 --> 15:58.827
You have to see him.

15:58.870 --> 16:01.830
[stirring music]

16:01.873 --> 16:08.924
♪

16:11.100 --> 16:13.842
This way.

16:23.025 --> 16:24.853
- Hey, how much longer?
I'm backing up downstairs.

16:24.896 --> 16:26.507
- I'm holding
this man's aorta together

16:26.550 --> 16:28.509
with string and Scotch tape.
I'm doing everything I can.

16:28.552 --> 16:30.554
- Well, your seven surgeries
waiting in my ED

16:30.598 --> 16:32.817
would disagree.
- Take it up with Max.

16:32.861 --> 16:35.472
- I would if I could find him.
- I'm going as fast as I can.

16:35.516 --> 16:37.039
I'm the only cardiothoracic
here.

16:37.083 --> 16:38.475
- Well, what about
one of your residents?

16:38.519 --> 16:40.303
I mean, the tall one
looked semi-competent.

16:40.347 --> 16:42.349
- Nottingham and, look,
for all these patients,

16:42.392 --> 16:44.133
this is the scariest day
of their lives.

16:44.177 --> 16:45.395
They woke up needing
major surgery,

16:45.439 --> 16:47.136
then they were thrown into
an ambulance

16:47.180 --> 16:49.225
and dragged across town so that
a doctor they don't know

16:49.269 --> 16:50.879
can cut open their hearts.

16:50.922 --> 16:53.229
They're trusting me, just like
Max is trusting me.

16:53.273 --> 16:54.839
And I'm not putting
that kind of pressure on

16:54.883 --> 16:56.841
a first-year resident straight
out of med school.

16:56.885 --> 16:58.495
Oh, we got a bleeder.

16:58.539 --> 17:00.323
Are the patients
downstairs stable?

17:00.367 --> 17:02.325
- Yeah.
- Then they can wait.

17:02.369 --> 17:03.979
- I am giving you one hour

17:04.023 --> 17:05.415
and then I am sending them
somewhere else.

17:05.459 --> 17:08.331
- All right, here we go.
[heart monitor beeping]

17:08.375 --> 17:09.506
- Suction.

17:09.550 --> 17:11.073
- Mrs. Monaghan,

17:11.117 --> 17:13.858
can you describe
your symptoms now?

17:13.902 --> 17:17.253
- [slowly] Dizzy!

17:17.297 --> 17:19.125
Are you even a real doctor?

17:19.168 --> 17:21.083
- Yes, and I'm trying
to help you.

17:21.127 --> 17:24.173
- Good, then give me something
for dizzy so I can go home.

17:24.217 --> 17:25.957
- I would love to do that,

17:26.001 --> 17:28.395
but I want to give you
the right something.

17:30.223 --> 17:33.574
I'll give you more time.
- You...

17:33.617 --> 17:35.880
- She's gonna be here all day.

17:35.924 --> 17:38.883
- Maybe, but fast and wrong
is not a service to her

17:38.927 --> 17:41.973
or to anyone else.

17:46.108 --> 17:49.459
Dr. Bloom?
What are you looking for?

17:49.503 --> 17:52.419
- Are you getting her
out of my ED?

17:52.462 --> 17:54.203
- Not as yet.

17:54.247 --> 17:55.378
- Can you get some
other patients out of here?

17:55.422 --> 17:57.902
Something's gotta give.

17:57.946 --> 18:01.515
Oh, and you should totally
give Ella your pastry.

18:01.558 --> 18:04.083
- So, you do understand
it was a harmless gesture.

18:04.126 --> 18:05.301
- Oh, I think
it's a huge mistake,

18:05.345 --> 18:08.609
but I want to see you suffer.

18:08.652 --> 18:10.567
- Oh!

18:10.611 --> 18:13.570
Laddus are not pastries!

18:13.614 --> 18:15.398
- It's like my college
sit-in days.

18:15.442 --> 18:18.488
Every chair occupied, so people
just lie on the floor.

18:18.532 --> 18:24.059
- Almost done.
Tilt and four hours to go.

18:24.103 --> 18:26.496
Go steal the chemo chairs
from onc'.

18:26.540 --> 18:28.716
- Oh, a grab and go.

18:28.759 --> 18:31.458
Also like my college days.
On it.

18:41.032 --> 18:43.948
- Jemma. Jemma, wait.
Hey, whoa, whoa. Are you okay?

18:43.992 --> 18:46.429
- No, I'm not okay.
None of this is okay.

18:46.473 --> 18:48.562
- Jemma, hang on.
We're trying our best here.

18:48.605 --> 18:51.434
Okay? It's an uphill battle.
I just--what?

18:51.478 --> 18:53.436
What's this?
What's happening here?

18:53.480 --> 18:55.525
- Transfers from the ED.
- No, no.

18:55.569 --> 18:57.136
Uh-uh, no.
No vacancies.

18:57.179 --> 18:58.659
We're all full up.
- So is the ED.

18:58.702 --> 19:00.182
- I'm not their safety valve.

19:00.226 --> 19:01.531
- All right, let's go.
- I just...

19:01.575 --> 19:03.664
[sighing]
Yeah, come in.

19:03.707 --> 19:06.275
This is exactly why we needed
the community garden.

19:06.319 --> 19:08.973
- What happened to the garden?
- I have to kill it.

19:09.017 --> 19:11.280
- You have been wanting
that garden for years.

19:11.324 --> 19:13.587
- Yeah, just not
with Volt Cola attached.

19:13.630 --> 19:16.677
- In India, Volt Cola builds
playgrounds, football fields,

19:16.720 --> 19:18.766
cricket pitches for kids
to play on.

19:18.809 --> 19:20.681
Which means land,
which takes money.

19:20.724 --> 19:23.597
Would a garden make
a difference to these kids too?

19:23.640 --> 19:26.600
- Yeah.

19:26.643 --> 19:29.037
Yeah, it would.

19:36.523 --> 19:39.090
- Tianna's cancer's back.

19:41.484 --> 19:44.661
Ewing's Sarcoma.

19:44.705 --> 19:47.534
It's extremely aggressive.

19:49.100 --> 19:51.494
I'm very sorry.

19:55.629 --> 19:59.763
- What about something
experimental?

19:59.807 --> 20:02.201
- Unfortunately,
there are no clinical trials

20:02.244 --> 20:03.550
for kids her age.

20:03.593 --> 20:06.596
- There has to be more
out there--um...

20:06.640 --> 20:09.643
other countries, um...

20:09.686 --> 20:11.732
there has to be something else.

20:15.736 --> 20:19.218
- [soflty] I think...

20:19.261 --> 20:21.394
that we should discuss...

20:21.437 --> 20:23.700
palliative care options.

20:27.791 --> 20:32.361
- How do we tell her?
- We don't.

20:32.405 --> 20:34.668
We can't.

20:34.711 --> 20:37.366
- Tianna is smart.

20:37.410 --> 20:42.197
She is asking questions.
She is looking for answers.

20:42.241 --> 20:46.288
The best course of act--
- I can't tell her.

20:46.332 --> 20:50.423
[stirring music]

20:50.466 --> 20:52.642
Can you?

20:52.686 --> 20:55.819
♪

20:55.863 --> 20:59.214
[crying softly]

21:03.740 --> 21:05.568
- Who are you? What'd you bring
this guy here for?

21:05.612 --> 21:07.483
- He's a doctor
and his name is Max.

21:07.527 --> 21:08.876
- You brought a doctor
to our house?

21:08.919 --> 21:10.573
- Hey, hey, hey.
He can help.

21:10.617 --> 21:12.096
- We don't need
his kind of help.

21:12.140 --> 21:13.837
- Give him a chance, Paul.

21:15.665 --> 21:19.756
- [wheezing]

21:19.800 --> 21:22.455
- Just...

21:22.498 --> 21:23.760
it's okay.

21:29.636 --> 21:34.336
- [panting]

21:34.380 --> 21:36.904
- Where are you from?

21:36.947 --> 21:39.298
Are you from the Midwest?

21:39.341 --> 21:42.649
- Hamilton, Ohio.
Born and raised.

21:42.692 --> 21:43.737
Why?

21:47.567 --> 21:49.656
- Vance, you may have
a fungal infection,

21:49.699 --> 21:52.311
and if it's the kind that
I think it is,

21:52.354 --> 21:53.747
we need to get you
into New Amsterdam right now.

21:53.790 --> 21:57.185
- No, man.
No hospital.

21:57.228 --> 21:58.752
- All right, what you got
to do now is just get the hell

21:58.795 --> 22:00.319
out of here.
- I don't know what you have

22:00.362 --> 22:01.711
against hospitals,
but if we don't take

22:01.755 --> 22:03.452
your brother to New Amsterdam
right now,

22:03.496 --> 22:05.236
he is going to die.
- Oh, that's exactly

22:05.280 --> 22:07.717
what the other doctors said
when Mom was sick.

22:07.761 --> 22:10.764
Except rather than help, they
just kept bringing bills.

22:10.807 --> 22:12.635
- We lost our apartment.

22:12.679 --> 22:16.857
The debt collectors
took the rest.

22:16.900 --> 22:18.946
- I promise you will
never see a single bill

22:18.989 --> 22:21.688
from New Amsterdam.

22:21.731 --> 22:24.386
What do you say, Vance?

22:24.430 --> 22:28.477
I took a gamble on you coming
here, leaving my own hospital.

22:28.521 --> 22:30.218
You want to take
a gamble on me?

22:33.917 --> 22:37.660
- Go away, man.

22:37.704 --> 22:40.184
- You heard him.

22:40.228 --> 22:42.491
Get out of here.

22:42.535 --> 22:45.494
[bleak music]

22:45.538 --> 22:48.497
[Vance wheezing]

22:48.541 --> 22:50.586
♪

22:50.630 --> 22:53.372
- [inhales sharply]

22:53.415 --> 22:55.722
♪

22:55.765 --> 22:58.899
[heart monitor beeping]

22:58.942 --> 23:01.467
[fast-paced music]

23:01.510 --> 23:04.948
- The graft's pulling taut.
It's too damn small.

23:04.992 --> 23:07.560
[water rushing]

23:11.564 --> 23:13.261
What?

23:13.304 --> 23:14.567
- Everyone is prepped,
so I thought I'd scrub in.

23:14.610 --> 23:16.656
- No.

23:16.699 --> 23:18.353
- I've watched you do
this surgery four times.

23:18.397 --> 23:19.789
I know to ligate
the internal mammary

23:19.833 --> 23:22.009
before transecting
the intercostal, I know--

23:22.052 --> 23:24.533
- I don't need you in here.
I need you out there.

23:24.577 --> 23:25.534
Go!

23:25.578 --> 23:28.885
[tense music]

23:28.929 --> 23:30.017
Suture.

23:30.060 --> 23:34.500
♪

23:38.678 --> 23:40.244
- Excuse me.

23:40.288 --> 23:42.508
Excuse me!
That is my chair!

23:42.551 --> 23:44.248
[elevator dings]

23:44.292 --> 23:46.425
Wha--

23:48.035 --> 23:50.733
- I said I ain't moving.
- You're not the only dumbass

23:50.777 --> 23:51.995
that needs space!

23:52.039 --> 23:53.432
[kisd shouting]

23:53.475 --> 23:55.912
all: Fight, fight, fight!

23:55.956 --> 23:57.827
- Thanks.
Over there.

23:57.871 --> 23:59.394
Not now.

23:59.438 --> 24:02.832
[patient coughs]

24:02.876 --> 24:04.704
♪

24:04.747 --> 24:07.489
- Goodwin!
Where the hell have you been?

24:07.533 --> 24:09.535
It's like a damn MASH unit
in here.

24:09.578 --> 24:11.450
- Dean, I had to take--
- What were you thinking?

24:11.493 --> 24:14.583
- Bloom, get all of
the department heads down here.

24:14.627 --> 24:16.846
Now.

24:16.890 --> 24:18.457
- Here you go, Doctor.
- [sighs]

24:21.155 --> 24:21.329
.

24:21.372 --> 24:23.897
- Clear up front?
- Yeah, we're good.

24:23.940 --> 24:26.029
- Okay, I'll make this quick
and clear.

24:26.073 --> 24:27.466
I screwed up.

24:27.509 --> 24:29.511
All this chaos, it's on me.

24:29.555 --> 24:31.470
I overcommitted us and then
went out looking for more.

24:31.513 --> 24:34.908
I thought I could help everyone
and ended up helping no one.

24:34.951 --> 24:36.910
I'm not asking for
understanding or forgiveness,

24:36.953 --> 24:40.304
but I am asking you
to help me fix this.

24:40.348 --> 24:42.568
So, here's the plan.

24:42.611 --> 24:45.048
Reynolds, I am sorry that I put
so much pressure on you.

24:45.092 --> 24:46.963
How can I take some of it off?

24:47.007 --> 24:48.835
- Are any of the surgeries
waiting in the ED stable enough

24:48.878 --> 24:50.358
to go to Mount Zion?
- Two.

24:50.401 --> 24:52.316
- I'll send them. Bloom,
anywhere there's an open bed,

24:52.360 --> 24:54.318
admit a patient to it.
Admit everyone you can.

24:54.362 --> 24:56.886
- And if we don't
get reimbursed for the beds?

24:56.930 --> 24:58.584
- I'll send Baptist the bill.
Iggy.

24:58.627 --> 25:00.237
- Captain?
- Take your patients

25:00.281 --> 25:02.239
to the cafeteria, to the roof,
for a walk--

25:02.283 --> 25:04.154
anywhere to keep them busy
and out of the ward.

25:04.198 --> 25:05.460
- Aye-aye.
- Sharpe.

25:05.504 --> 25:07.593
- I know what I have to do.
- Great.

25:07.636 --> 25:09.986
Any questions?

25:10.030 --> 25:13.512
Any questions not about
Kapoor's laddu situation?

25:13.555 --> 25:15.122
- No.
- Go.

25:20.214 --> 25:24.218
- Max, I don't know how you're
gonna pull this off.

25:24.261 --> 25:27.438
- We're all gonna
work together.

25:27.482 --> 25:28.962
Including you.

25:29.005 --> 25:32.400
I could really use your help,
Dr. Fulton.

25:38.624 --> 25:43.280
- The flat metal part goes on
the patient's chest.

25:54.335 --> 25:57.556
- [inaudible]

25:57.599 --> 26:00.907
- How're you holding up?

26:00.950 --> 26:05.564
- I thought getting the news
would be the hard part, but...

26:05.607 --> 26:08.915
telling Tianna's
a million times harder.

26:12.527 --> 26:15.051
- You shouldn't have to.

26:15.095 --> 26:17.967
You be her mum.

26:18.011 --> 26:21.536
I'll be her doctor.

26:21.580 --> 26:23.320
I'll tell her.

26:29.979 --> 26:32.068
- In for a little treat here.

26:32.112 --> 26:35.028
Come on. Come on out.

26:35.071 --> 26:36.682
Okay.

26:36.725 --> 26:39.336
So, it's not a garden,
but, you know,

26:39.380 --> 26:41.469
it's outside.
It's fresh-air therapy.

26:41.512 --> 26:44.907
We got a wonderful view
of the city, so, you know,

26:44.951 --> 26:48.476
spread out, feel the space.
Find your own spot, all right?

26:50.478 --> 26:52.262
Jemma, hi.

26:52.306 --> 26:54.613
What's going on?
Talk to me.

26:54.656 --> 26:56.919
- There's nothing to say.

26:56.963 --> 26:59.356
- Well, I heard that
Blanca's background check

26:59.400 --> 27:01.445
came through clean.

27:01.489 --> 27:04.448
That's good news, right?

27:04.492 --> 27:09.105
- Yeah.

27:09.149 --> 27:11.455
But, like, the site visit
keeps getting pushed back.

27:11.499 --> 27:13.153
It isn't for months.

27:13.196 --> 27:14.981
And there's, like,
100 other things

27:15.024 --> 27:17.418
that could go wrong
before I get out of here.

27:17.461 --> 27:19.028
- Hey.

27:19.072 --> 27:20.987
Are those facts
or those feelings?

27:22.684 --> 27:25.513
- It's feelings.
- Right, they're feelings,

27:25.556 --> 27:28.168
so why don't we try
sticking to the facts?

27:28.211 --> 27:30.474
Okay, I'll make some
phone calls.

27:30.518 --> 27:33.477
We're going to get you
the home you deserve.

27:33.521 --> 27:36.002
I promise.

27:36.742 --> 27:38.265
All right.

27:42.356 --> 27:45.315
[intriguing music]

27:45.359 --> 27:52.409
♪

27:58.328 --> 28:01.027
- Dr. Frome?

28:06.467 --> 28:08.730
- Don't we have wheelchairs
for that?

28:08.774 --> 28:10.427
- They're all taken,
but don't need one.

28:10.471 --> 28:12.081
This is how we did it
in Afghanistan.

28:12.125 --> 28:14.170
My man right here's
on his way to X-ray.

28:14.214 --> 28:15.694
Got a lateral malleolus
fracture

28:15.737 --> 28:17.260
playing indoor soccer,
but he's going to be fine.

28:17.304 --> 28:18.305
Right, Camden?

28:18.348 --> 28:20.437
- Did you take my ibuprofen?

28:20.481 --> 28:22.396
- Yeah. Thanks

28:29.795 --> 28:33.407
- Ah, Dr. Kapoor.
- Oh, Dean.

28:33.450 --> 28:35.191
- Mrs. Monaghan
has been telling me

28:35.235 --> 28:37.063
a very interesting story.

28:37.106 --> 28:40.153
- How you don't seem
to understand the word "dizzy."

28:41.720 --> 28:44.635
- I do understand. Do you?

28:44.679 --> 28:46.159
- Do you see what I mean?

28:46.202 --> 28:48.596
I should have walked out
of here an hour ago.

28:48.639 --> 28:51.207
- Why didn't you?
- Because when I tried

28:51.251 --> 28:54.167
to stand up, I feel like
I'm going to fall over.

28:54.210 --> 28:55.734
Like my feet aren't even there.

28:58.737 --> 29:02.610
- Mrs. Monaghan, you have
Guillain-Barré syndrome.

29:02.653 --> 29:04.307
- Excuse me?

29:04.351 --> 29:06.309
- The anti-bodies your system
made to fight your cold

29:06.353 --> 29:08.137
are attacking the nerves
in your feet.

29:08.181 --> 29:10.139
That's why you can't feel them.

29:10.183 --> 29:12.185
- Uh...

29:12.228 --> 29:15.275
- I can now officially admit
you and get you taken care of.

29:20.454 --> 29:21.629
[door banging]
- Help!

29:21.672 --> 29:23.500
We--we need help!

29:23.544 --> 29:26.329
- [retching]
- [gasping] Max--Max...

29:26.373 --> 29:29.724
Max said he would help him.
Max? Max?

29:29.768 --> 29:31.595
- We've got an arterial bleed.

29:31.639 --> 29:34.860
Ready an intubation tray and
page Max to Trauma One, now!

29:34.903 --> 29:36.426
- Max!
- Come on, stay with us.

29:36.470 --> 29:40.256
Come on.
- [crying]

29:40.300 --> 29:42.563
[indistinct conversation]

29:42.606 --> 29:44.478
- Class-one airway.
Get 20 milligrams of Etomidate

29:44.521 --> 29:46.436
and 100 milligrams
Succinylcholine

29:46.480 --> 29:48.612
and let's start
a propofol drip.

29:48.656 --> 29:50.876
[Vance rasping,
monitor beeping]

29:50.919 --> 29:53.443
- Gonna be a 7.5
on the hockey stick.

29:53.487 --> 29:55.663
- 7.5 on the hockey stick.

30:03.236 --> 30:05.542
- I'm in.

30:08.458 --> 30:11.548
[machine pumping]

30:17.772 --> 30:20.819
- Now we find the bleeder.

30:23.473 --> 30:26.520
[machine whirs]

30:27.434 --> 30:29.392
[machine beeps]

30:29.436 --> 30:30.829
There it is.

30:30.872 --> 30:32.831
The bleeding is coming from
that bronchiole.

30:34.571 --> 30:36.443
- Don't say it.

30:36.486 --> 30:38.619
- We need Reynolds.

30:41.274 --> 30:43.319
- Uh, elbow deep
in a tricky closure.

30:43.363 --> 30:45.321
- A man's bleeding out
in the ED.

30:45.365 --> 30:47.236
- Is this your idea
of relieving pressure?

30:47.280 --> 30:48.890
- I know, Floyd. I'm sorry.
I don't know what else to do.

30:48.934 --> 30:50.674
I don't know who else to ask.
- Well, I can't be

30:50.718 --> 30:52.241
in two places at once.
- Well, I hope you can

30:52.285 --> 30:54.417
figure out how, or someone
is going to die.

31:02.077 --> 31:02.295
.

31:02.338 --> 31:04.863
- Thank you.
- Clamp.

31:06.429 --> 31:09.084
[machine slurping liquid]

31:09.128 --> 31:11.739
- Blood pressure's dropping.
- Push more fluid.

31:11.782 --> 31:14.220
- Got two liters wide open.
- It's not enough.

31:14.263 --> 31:16.787
- Grab a bag of O-negative out
of the trauma fridge.

31:16.831 --> 31:18.746
There's too much blood.
I can't see anything.

31:18.789 --> 31:19.921
- There's a pumper in there
somewhere.

31:19.965 --> 31:21.053
I just can't find it.

31:21.096 --> 31:23.882
Suction.

31:23.925 --> 31:25.796
Will you get the Richardson and
lift up

31:25.840 --> 31:27.146
the middle lobe, please?

31:28.843 --> 31:31.280
There it is.
I got that bad boy.

31:31.324 --> 31:33.979
Hey Max, can you give me
a little light over here?

31:35.806 --> 31:37.417
There we go.
- It's ready.

31:41.073 --> 31:43.423
- Bleeding stopped.

31:43.466 --> 31:48.297
- Heart rate's steady.
Oxygenation stabilizing.

31:48.341 --> 31:51.431
- Nice work, boys.

31:51.474 --> 31:53.694
- So, what, you just let
Dr. Fernandez

31:53.737 --> 31:55.304
just bleed out in the OR?

31:55.348 --> 31:59.308
- I left him in the hands
of a top-notch surgeon.

32:01.006 --> 32:05.401
[heart monitor beeping,
indistinct conversation]

32:05.445 --> 32:07.838
- One more running suture.

32:07.882 --> 32:11.277
- Respiration is spontaneous.

32:11.320 --> 32:13.061
- That should hold.

32:13.105 --> 32:17.283
- All right!
[cheers and applause]

32:36.389 --> 32:38.869
- Surgeons landed at JFK
an hour ago.

32:38.913 --> 32:40.871
Baptist is up and running.

32:40.915 --> 32:42.873
- You did it, Max.

32:42.917 --> 32:46.442
It was fun,
being back in the trenches.

32:47.878 --> 32:50.359
And Max...

32:50.403 --> 32:53.058
don't ever do that again.

33:00.543 --> 33:03.764
- Good news: Vance will be
in the ICU a few days,

33:03.807 --> 33:07.376
then a course of pills, then he
should make a full recovery.

33:07.420 --> 33:08.899
- What was wrong with him?

33:08.943 --> 33:11.163
- Histoplasmosis.
It's a fungal infection

33:11.206 --> 33:12.991
we see in the soil
around Ohio.

33:13.034 --> 33:15.906
It must have been dormant
in Vance his whole life,

33:15.950 --> 33:17.299
and I'm sure living
on the streets

33:17.343 --> 33:19.388
weakened his immune system.
The fungus reemerged,

33:19.432 --> 33:21.347
and attacked his lungs
and his liver.

33:21.390 --> 33:23.740
I would like to test
you both as well.

33:23.784 --> 33:27.048
- We can't possibly pay
for all this.

33:27.092 --> 33:28.354
- You don't have to.

33:28.397 --> 33:30.965
This is why
public hospitals exist.

33:31.009 --> 33:32.967
This is why I work here.

33:33.011 --> 33:36.144
This is why all
these doctors work here.

33:36.188 --> 33:39.104
We don't say no to anyone.

33:39.147 --> 33:40.496
We don't know how.

33:40.540 --> 33:42.368
[stirring music]

33:42.411 --> 33:47.503
♪

33:47.547 --> 33:49.853
- Thank you.

33:49.897 --> 33:52.943
♪

33:52.987 --> 33:56.034
- Casey, hydrate.
- Why?

33:56.077 --> 33:57.948
- Because water plays
a vital role

33:57.992 --> 33:59.776
in nearly
every bodily function.

33:59.820 --> 34:00.951
- Mm.

34:00.995 --> 34:03.780
Ah, I needed that.

34:03.824 --> 34:06.044
- My ibuprofen
wasn't ibuprofen.

34:06.087 --> 34:08.524
It was Adderall.

34:08.568 --> 34:11.005
- That explains why I thought
I was covered in lice.

34:11.049 --> 34:12.833
And my headache
never went away.

34:12.876 --> 34:15.096
- I have ADHD.
- Listen, you don't have to--

34:15.140 --> 34:16.489
- I had it my whole life.

34:16.532 --> 34:18.273
Adderall got me
through med school,

34:18.317 --> 34:19.927
through my residency.

34:19.970 --> 34:21.494
I mean, I couldn't do
this job without it.

34:21.537 --> 34:23.496
- So, why do you keep it
in an ibuprofen bottle?

34:26.151 --> 34:28.283
You're killing yourself
for this job.

34:28.327 --> 34:30.894
- Everyone here is.

34:32.505 --> 34:35.508
- Everyone looks sad.

34:36.944 --> 34:41.905
- Sweetheart...
your cancer is back.

34:47.955 --> 34:50.088
Tianna.

34:50.131 --> 34:52.090
You asked what
it's like when you die.

34:54.179 --> 34:57.530
I think that it's like this.

35:02.883 --> 35:05.842
[gentle music]

35:05.886 --> 35:11.370
♪

35:11.413 --> 35:14.024
Come.

35:26.341 --> 35:30.171
So, when it happens,

35:30.215 --> 35:34.001
you won't be able to see
your mum and dad,

35:34.044 --> 35:36.873
and they won't be able
to see you.

35:36.917 --> 35:40.921
But they will always be there.

35:45.012 --> 35:48.450
- And I'll always be here?

35:49.408 --> 35:51.932
- Yes.

35:51.975 --> 35:56.589
You'll never stop thinking
of each other.

35:56.632 --> 36:01.159
You'll never stop talking
to each other.

36:01.202 --> 36:04.379
You'll just be on
a different side of the room.

36:10.559 --> 36:15.085
- Mommy, can you hear me?

36:15.129 --> 36:19.394
- Yes, baby doll.
- We can hear you, little one.

36:19.438 --> 36:21.918
- I can hear you too.

36:21.962 --> 36:29.012
♪

36:41.068 --> 36:43.679
[faint conversation]

36:43.723 --> 36:46.682
[The Oh Hellos'
"Hello My Old Heart"]

36:46.726 --> 36:49.642
♪

36:49.685 --> 36:52.427
♪ Hello, my old heart

36:52.471 --> 36:55.125
♪ How have you been?

36:55.169 --> 37:00.479
♪ Are you still there
inside my chest? ♪

37:00.522 --> 37:03.482
♪ I've been so worried

37:03.525 --> 37:10.140
♪ You've been so still,
barely beating at all ♪

37:10.184 --> 37:13.970
[bottle clinking]
- You okay?

37:14.014 --> 37:15.711
- ♪ Don't leave me
here alone ♪

37:15.755 --> 37:18.323
♪ Don't tell me how we grow

37:18.366 --> 37:21.108
- I took the hard road.

37:21.151 --> 37:23.153
- ♪ Oh, oh-oh

37:23.197 --> 37:26.418
- And?

37:26.461 --> 37:28.463
- Better views.

37:28.507 --> 37:30.204
- ♪ I wanna find a home

37:30.248 --> 37:33.294
♪ And I wanna share it
with you ♪

37:33.338 --> 37:37.255
♪

37:37.298 --> 37:41.694
[vocalizing]

37:41.737 --> 37:46.786
♪ Hello, my old heart

37:46.829 --> 37:50.180
[brightening indie rock]

37:50.224 --> 37:57.231
♪

38:05.718 --> 38:08.024
♪ Hello

38:08.068 --> 38:10.505
♪ Old heart

38:10.549 --> 38:12.246
- You know, my attending
wouldn't even let me look

38:12.290 --> 38:14.553
in the OR the first three
months of my residency?

38:14.596 --> 38:17.817
[chuckling] I can still hear
him in my head.

38:17.860 --> 38:20.385
[gruffly] "Reynolds, you're
more likely to cut yourself

38:20.428 --> 38:23.213
than the patient."

38:23.257 --> 38:26.216
I don't know.
Old habits die hard, I guess.

38:26.260 --> 38:29.437
- Well, the difference is
you trained these residents.

38:29.481 --> 38:34.442
- Yeah, well, but--you know,
if something had gone wrong...

38:34.486 --> 38:37.140
- Okay, do you know
what feels even better

38:37.184 --> 38:39.099
than being in control?

38:39.142 --> 38:41.536
Letting go of it.

38:49.414 --> 38:52.373
[SYML's "Where's My Love"]

38:52.417 --> 38:55.376
[gentle acoustic music]

38:55.420 --> 39:00.642
♪

39:00.686 --> 39:04.603
Don't start what you
can't finish.

39:10.304 --> 39:12.175
- ♪ Cold

39:12.219 --> 39:17.398
- Well, on the bright side,
I can finally take up fencing.

39:18.617 --> 39:21.402
♪ She glides away

39:21.446 --> 39:24.100
- In a few weeks, we'll start
chemo in the morning

39:24.144 --> 39:25.754
and radiation at night.

39:25.798 --> 39:27.626
- By few weeks, you mean--
- Two.

39:27.669 --> 39:29.192
- 'Cause sometimes
a few can mean--

39:29.236 --> 39:30.890
- Two.
- Right.

39:30.933 --> 39:35.764
- ♪ Does she know
that we bleed the same? ♪

39:35.808 --> 39:38.419
- [sighs]
There's so much to do.

39:38.463 --> 39:40.421
- ♪ Don't wanna cry,
but I break that way ♪

39:40.465 --> 39:45.252
- You're going
to have to prioritize.

39:45.295 --> 39:47.472
- You mean
start saying no?

39:47.515 --> 39:52.433
- I mean
start saying yes.

39:52.477 --> 39:55.784
To you.

39:55.828 --> 39:57.917
What do you need, Max?

39:57.960 --> 40:00.659
[ethereal vocalizations]

40:00.702 --> 40:07.579
♪

40:16.892 --> 40:18.633
♪ I

40:18.677 --> 40:22.507
♪ Have got a fear

40:22.550 --> 40:26.641
♪ Oh, in my blood

40:26.685 --> 40:28.948
♪ Cold

40:28.991 --> 40:32.473
♪ Sheets

40:32.517 --> 40:35.694
♪ Oh, where's my love

40:35.737 --> 40:37.826
♪ I am

40:37.870 --> 40:39.524
♪ Searching high

40:39.567 --> 40:41.221
♪ I'm searching low

40:41.264 --> 40:45.355
♪ In the night
[alarm rings]

40:45.399 --> 40:51.405
♪ Ooh, does she know
that we bleed the same? ♪

40:53.363 --> 40:59.674
♪ Ooh, don't want to cry,
but I break that way ♪

40:59.718 --> 41:03.461
♪

41:03.504 --> 41:06.899
♪ Did she run away,
did she run away? ♪

41:06.942 --> 41:12.774
♪ I don't know

41:12.818 --> 41:16.256
♪ If she ran away,
if she ran away ♪

41:16.299 --> 41:19.302
♪ Come back home

41:19.346 --> 41:26.396
♪

41:26.745 --> 41:29.791
- Max.

41:32.446 --> 41:36.624
It's 9:30.
You're going to be late.

41:36.668 --> 41:40.454
- [inhales]
No, I'm not.

41:40.498 --> 41:44.545
- Oh, my God.
Did you get fired?

41:44.589 --> 41:47.766
That was fast, even for you.

41:47.809 --> 41:52.553
- I'm taking the day off.

41:52.597 --> 41:56.557
Thought I'd spend the day
here...

41:56.601 --> 41:57.732
with you.

41:57.776 --> 42:03.782
♪
